{
    "text": "Some catch",
    "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:16:52 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "I reread the first chapter of Catch-22 just now in a 46-year-old purple paperback with thick blocks of pages sliding out. On the first page, Yossarian is revealed to be a malingerer who handily always runs a 101 degree temperature. It is within reach for Yossarian to sit out the war in the infirmary, and if the place were not populated by truly sick people and loud patriots who seem never to have asked themselves a hard question in their lives, he and one or two other malingerers might have pulled it off.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:16:58 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a001658"
        },
        {
            "text": "A team of doctors come by every day, scrutinizing Yossarian's health. He did not quite have jaundice, and he was not quite free of it either. Fitting no medical category, the doctors were paralyzed by his case. They'd put his clipboard back on the hook and walk on.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:25:12 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a002512"
        },
        {
            "text": "And there is the soldier in white, who receives almost no medical treatment. He is completely covered in white bandages and castes, his limbs are in traction, help up by weights at the four corners of the bed. A nurse comes by and balances a thermometer on the ragged opening in the bandages where his mouth must be. Fluids drip into one tube and out another, emptying the elevated bottle and filling the lower one. One of the patriots sits nearby jabbering at him morning, afternoon, and evening. There seems to be no hope for him.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:27:07 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a002707"
        },
        {
            "text": "So a good number of the book's worries are on the table from the start. The war will kill whoever it wants to kill, some soldiers try to find a way out, others are caught in its web, some hardly seem to notice the stakes. Experts blinded by their expertise walk the corridors doing nothing because the world doesn't fit the neat categories of their training. Some people are prepared to disobey to save their lives.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:30:18 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a003018"
        },
        {
            "text": "And the chaplain, a sensitive soul who tries to minister to those in need, keenly realizes that there is not much he can do. He is worn down by this from the first.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:32:29 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a003229"
        },
        {
            "text": "More characters will come on stage, more events will unfold, but the heart of the novel is present in the first several pages. Set up the elements clearly and start the clock ticking. Short stories often work this same way.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:33:20 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/001652.html?title=someCatch#a003320"
        }
    ]
}

{
    "text": "Beavers and wolves",
    "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:37:12 GMT",
    "type": "outline",
    "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves",
    "subs": [
        {
            "text": "Everybody may have heard about the wolves of Yellowstone by now. Reintroduced some years ago, they changed the behavior of the wild grazing animals they hunted. The plant life had a chance to grow more bountiful because of that, and from there insects and birds. The banks of creeks were more firmly held by the roots of plants, so spring rains acted differently upon the land than in the previous, stripped-down state. Etc.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:37:39 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves#a003739"
        },
        {
            "text": "Nature, we see from cases like this, has powers of resilience, if given a chance.  Nature does better when more complex natural systems are allowed to play out their ancient ways.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:39:51 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves#a003951"
        },
        {
            "text": "In today's NT Times, a similar story. A rancher out west grew tired of killing beavers, and so beavers returned to his land, built their dams, kept more water in place in drought times, supported more plants which supported more insects, birds, and mammals. In flood times, the dams mitigated the onrush of spring melt waters. Nature grew more complex, nature handled more things, because we allowed nature to be more complex.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:41:06 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves#a004106"
        },
        {
            "text": "Hundreds of miles east of there, the row crops await rains and irrigation, fertilizer and pesticide. Species variety diminishes, groundwater is poisoned by runoff from CAFOs, underground aquifers are whittled away, likely never to return. The ideal there is one species of plant this year, corn or soybeans, and the reverse next year. The end of nature doing what nature knows how to do.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:43:05 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves#a004305"
        },
        {
            "text": "The clues are everywhere. We tore up 60% of the grass in our lawn and replaced it mainly with native perennials. Now, most obvious of all the results, there are varieties of bees in our yard that we had never seen before. The bees know how to come back, if there is something to come back to.",
            "created": "Wed, 07 Sep 2022 00:46:03 GMT",
            "permalink": "http://oldschool.scripting.com/KenSmith/2022/09/06/003712.html?title=beaversAndWolves#a004603"
        }
    ]
}

